"""
ipc_fourcore_check — host-only end-to-end harness for the wave-3 4-core NVMe
FW IPC pipeline (design contract: doc/05_design/hardware/nvme_fw_multicore/
fourcore_ipc_index_handle_design.md §6 four-core partition, §8 dataplane
selftest).

Simulates all 4 cores (HIL/FTL/FIL/NAND) as round-robin step functions over a
single host-side `[i64]` array standing in for the rv32 `_ipc_shm` region —
the SAME state machines (logic_fourcore_core.spl, logic_ipc_ring_core.spl,
logic_buf_pool_core.spl, logic_nand_region_core.spl) the rv32 SMP boot path
(L6) will run; only the shm accessor differs (bounds-checked array indexing
here vs. the asm-stub load/store externs on rv32). Arrays are legal here:
this file is host-only, never imported by entry.spl / logic.spl (same
exemption const_drift_check.spl / buf_pool_check.spl rely on).

Deliberately NOT part of the boot-linked import graph.

Run: timeout 300 bin/simple run examples/09_embedded/simpleos_nvme_fw/fw_rv32/ipc_fourcore_check.spl
Gate: prints "IPC FOURCORE CHECK PASS" and exits rc=0; any oracle failure or
step-budget exhaustion prints "IPC FOURCORE CHECK FAIL" and exits rc=1 (same
mechanism as ipc_ring_check.spl).

Completions are correlated by TAG only (like an NVMe CID), not by re-parsing
the opcode field on the way back up — HIL's own local bookkeeping (which
lba/expected-data a tag maps to, tracked directly in the selftest script)
plays the role real firmware gets from its own outstanding-command table.
The opcode field IS translated at each DOWNWARD hop (OP_WRITE->OP_PROG->
NOP_PROG etc., per design §4) since that is what routes the message; on the
way back up each hop only rewrites the STATUS field and relays
opcode/tag/w1/w2/w3 unchanged — HIL never needs to re-derive the original
HIL-facing opcode from a NOP_*/OP_PROG value.

Deviation from the wave-3 lane spec text (reported per the agent guide's
"deviate + report" rule): the spec sketches `drv_ring_push(...) -> (shm, ok)`
/ `drv_ring_pop(...)` as tuple-returning drivers. The agent guide's language
landmines flag anonymous-tuple returns as decaying to garbage in this
interpreter, so this file avoids tuples entirely: `drv_ring_push` returns
only the mutated shm (callers must check shm_ring_push_ok first — the
backpressure law is enforced at the call site via the pure ring-verdict
fns, which is where the design doc says the "compute verdict, only act if
ok" decision belongs anyway), and pop is split into a pure
`drv_ring_peek_word` (read, no mutation) plus `drv_ring_pop` (advance-only
mutation).

── W4b: statement-like corostate dispatch overlay (design contract: doc/
05_design/hardware/nvme_fw_coroutine/coroutine_statemachine_design.md, lane
table §6 row W4b) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
hil_step/ftl_step/fil_step/nand_step below are rewritten as corostate
dispatchers over logic_coro_core.spl's shared state vocabulary, WITHOUT
changing a single message/ring/pool statement (every dataplane statement
that used to live directly in those 4 fns now lives, byte-for-byte, in a
`*_body`/`*_reap` helper called from exactly one dispatch branch). The rv32
shm layout (logic_ipc_layout_core.spl, COROSTATE_BASE=8448) is a LATER lane
(W4c) and is intentionally untouched here — this file pre-stages the same
4 words plus a debug trace ring PURELY in harness-local host memory (see
HOST_COROSTATE_BASE/HOST_TRACE_* below), never through shm_get/shm_put
(which stay bound to the landed ipc_shm_words()=8448 ceiling on purpose, so
any accidental drift would fail loudly rather than silently write past the
real layout once W4c lands).

Deviations from the design doc's illustrative pattern, documented per the
same "deviate + report" rule as above:
- hil_submit_write/read/flush stay OUTSIDE the corostate machine (untouched,
  still callable back-to-back with no scheduler steps between them, per the
  file's existing stage-3 backpressure contract). CS_SUBMIT is therefore a
  pass-through phase for hil_step (nothing to do — the actual submit already
  happened via a direct call) that always advances to CS_REAP; CS_VERIFY is
  likewise a pass-through that only re-checks the halt flag (the actual
  tag/status/data verification is the selftest's own inline checks, which
  run between hil_step's REAP and the next scheduler tick).
- Because CS_SUBMIT/CS_VERIFY advance unconditionally every tick regardless
  of whether a completion has actually arrived, HIL's REAP phase is not
  guaranteed to be the ACTIVE phase on the exact tick a completion first
  lands in R_FTL2HIL (SUBMIT/VERIFY may be "in the way"). The selftest's
  single explicit `hil_step(shm)` call after each drain relies on HIL being
  in CS_REAP right then, so `drain_until_ftl2hil_ready` below gained a
  second wait condition (HIL corostate == CS_REAP) alongside the original
  ring-ready check — a harness-only scheduling fix, zero dataplane change.
- Workers (FTL/FIL/NAND) collapse CS_PUMP_FWD/CS_PUMP_BACK into a same-tick
  self-loop back to CS_IDLE: the *_step_idle wrapper calls the existing body
  unconditionally (unchanged behavior) and then either self-transitions
  CS_IDLE->CS_IDLE or, once the halt flag is observed, CS_IDLE->
  CS_HALT_DRAIN — never labeling a movement as FWD/BACK, since deriving that
  label precisely would require duplicating the body's internal nested
  backpressure branches outside it (a correctness risk for a label the host
  harness's oracles never need — design §5's HIL-cycle oracle is the only
  one this lane requires). The dispatchers still carry explicit
  CS_PUMP_FWD/CS_PUMP_BACK branches (pass-through back to CS_IDLE) for full
  vocabulary coverage; they are unreached by this harness, same hardening-
  honesty convention as nand_step's NOP_ERASE branch below.
"""

use logic_ipc_layout_core.*
use logic_ipc_msg_core.*
use logic_ipc_ring_core.*
use logic_buf_pool_core.*
use logic_nand_region_core.*
use logic_fourcore_core.*
use logic_coro_core.*
use std.io_runtime.{exit}

# ── W4b harness-local corostate + trace-ring overlay (pre-stages the W4c
# layout append; logic_ipc_layout_core.spl is INTENTIONALLY untouched — see
# file header). Lives past the landed ipc_shm_words()=8448 ceiling, so it
# uses its own hc_get/hc_put accessors (NOT shm_get/shm_put, which stay
# bound to the landed layout on purpose) and its own bounds check against
# HOST_SHM_WORDS(). ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn HOST_COROSTATE_BASE() -> i64:
    8448

fn HIL_CORE() -> i64:
    0

fn FTL_CORE() -> i64:
    1

fn FIL_CORE() -> i64:
    2

fn NAND_CORE() -> i64:
    3

fn host_core_valid(core: i64) -> i32:
    if core < 0:
        return 0
    if core > NAND_CORE():
        return 0
    1

fn host_corostate_idx(core: i64) -> i64:
    if host_core_valid(core) == 0:
        return ipc_null_idx()
    HOST_COROSTATE_BASE() + core

# 16-entry transition trace ring, right after the 4 corostate words: each
# slot holds one packed (core, cur, next) triple as core*100 + cur*10 +
# next (core 0..3, state ids 0..8 — both fit single decimal digits, so the
# packing is lossless and trivially decodable: core = packed/100, cur =
# (packed/10)%10, next = packed%10).
fn HOST_TRACE_BASE() -> i64:
    HOST_COROSTATE_BASE() + 4

fn HOST_TRACE_DEPTH() -> i64:
    16

fn HOST_TRACE_CURSOR_IDX() -> i64:
    HOST_TRACE_BASE() + HOST_TRACE_DEPTH()

fn HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX() -> i64:
    HOST_TRACE_CURSOR_IDX() + 1

fn HOST_SHM_WORDS() -> i64:
    HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX() + 1

fn hc_idx_valid(idx: i64) -> i32:
    if idx < 0:
        return 0
    if idx >= HOST_SHM_WORDS():
        return 0
    1

fn hc_get(shm: [i64], idx: i64) -> i64:
    if hc_idx_valid(idx) == 0:
        return -1
    shm[idx]

fn hc_put(shm: [i64], idx: i64, v: i64) -> [i64]:
    if hc_idx_valid(idx) == 0:
        return shm
    var s = shm
    s[idx] = v
    s

# Oldest-to-newest walk over the trace ring's currently-valid entries
# (logical_i = 0 is oldest, HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX()-1 is newest); handles
# the pre-wrap (count < depth, oldest is slot 0) and post-wrap (count ==
# depth, oldest is the slot the cursor is about to overwrite next) cases.
fn trace_entry_at(shm: [i64], logical_i: i64) -> i64:
    val count: i64 = hc_get(shm, HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX())
    val cursor: i64 = hc_get(shm, HOST_TRACE_CURSOR_IDX())
    var oldest_slot: i64 = 0
    if count >= HOST_TRACE_DEPTH():
        oldest_slot = cursor
    val slot: i64 = (oldest_slot + logical_i) % HOST_TRACE_DEPTH()
    hc_get(shm, HOST_TRACE_BASE() + slot)

fn coro_trace_push(shm: [i64], core: i64, cur: i64, next: i64) -> [i64]:
    val packed: i64 = core * 100 + cur * 10 + next
    val cursor: i64 = hc_get(shm, HOST_TRACE_CURSOR_IDX())
    var s = shm
    s = hc_put(s, HOST_TRACE_BASE() + cursor, packed)
    s = hc_put(s, HOST_TRACE_CURSOR_IDX(), (cursor + 1) % HOST_TRACE_DEPTH())
    val cnt: i64 = hc_get(s, HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX())
    var new_cnt: i64 = cnt
    if cnt < HOST_TRACE_DEPTH():
        new_cnt = cnt + 1
    hc_put(s, HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX(), new_cnt)

# The ONE shared transition helper every dispatcher below must go through
# (design §3/§4: drivers never store a corostate word except through this
# path). Fail-closed: an illegal verdict FAILs the whole harness the same
# way rv32's ipc_fatal would (design §3), never a silent/garbage state
# write. On success: commits the new corostate word AND appends one trace-
# ring entry, so "one dispatch call -> at most one transition" also means
# "at most one trace entry" (design §5 debug surface).
fn coro_do_transition(shm: [i64], core: i64, cur: i64, next: i64) -> [i64]:
    val verdict: i64 = coro_transition_verdict(cur, next)
    if verdict == -1:
        print "  FAIL: illegal corostate transition (fail-closed halt, design SS3)"
        exit(1)
        return shm
    var s = shm
    s = hc_put(s, host_corostate_idx(core), verdict)
    coro_trace_push(s, core, cur, verdict)

# Shared CS_HALT_DRAIN phase (design §3: the ONLY exit is CS_HALT_DRAIN ->
# CS_PARKED, once drain is complete). "Drain complete" is the same global
# all_rings_empty() the selftest itself already uses for its own halt+drain
# oracle (design §6 core_should_halt has the same "aggregate of its rings"
# looseness) — reused here rather than re-deriving a per-core notion.
fn coro_halt_drain_phase(shm: [i64], core: i64, cs: i64) -> [i64]:
    if all_rings_empty(shm) == 0:
        return shm
    coro_do_transition(shm, core, cs, CS_PARKED())

fn all_corostates_parked(shm: [i64]) -> i32:
    if hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(HIL_CORE())) != CS_PARKED():
        return 0
    if hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(FTL_CORE())) != CS_PARKED():
        return 0
    if hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(FIL_CORE())) != CS_PARKED():
        return 0
    if hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(NAND_CORE())) != CS_PARKED():
        return 0
    1

# Oracle (a) helper (design §5): scan the trace ring's valid entries
# oldest->newest, filter to HIL-only, and match the canonical 3-transition
# sequence for one write's full journey: CS_BOOT->CS_SUBMIT (packed 6),
# CS_SUBMIT->CS_REAP (packed 67), CS_REAP->CS_VERIFY (packed 78), in that
# exact order (other cores' interleaved entries are skipped, not required
# to be absent).
fn hil_seq_check(shm: [i64]) -> i32:
    val count: i64 = hc_get(shm, HOST_TRACE_COUNT_IDX())
    var matched: i64 = 0
    var i: i64 = 0
    while i < count:
        val packed: i64 = trace_entry_at(shm, i)
        val core: i64 = packed / 100
        if core == HIL_CORE():
            if matched == 0 and packed == 6:
                matched = 1
            if matched == 1 and packed == 67:
                matched = 2
            if matched == 2 and packed == 78:
                matched = 3
        i = i + 1
    if matched == 3:
        return 1
    0

# ── shm accessors (bounds-checked, same convention the rv32 asm-stub
# wrappers will use) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn shm_new() -> [i64]:
    # HOST_SHM_WORDS() (not ipc_shm_words()) so the harness-local corostate
    # + trace-ring words past the landed 8448 ceiling exist too. All-zero
    # init already gives every corostate word CS_BOOT()==0 and an empty
    # trace ring (cursor=0, count=0) for free — no extra init needed.
    var s: [i64] = [0 for i in 0..HOST_SHM_WORDS()]
    var i: i64 = 0
    while i < buf_pool_capacity():
        s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_next_idx(i), buf_pool_init_next_val(i))
        i = i + 1
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_free_head_idx(), 0)
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx(), 0)
    s

fn shm_get(shm: [i64], idx: i64) -> i64:
    if shm_idx_valid(idx) == 0:
        return -1
    shm[idx]

fn shm_put(shm: [i64], idx: i64, v: i64) -> [i64]:
    if shm_idx_valid(idx) == 0:
        return shm
    var s = shm
    s[idx] = v
    s

# ── ring driver (§4 publish/consume order) ────────────────────────────────────
# SPSC ownership: TAIL is written only by the producer (drv_ring_push), HEAD
# only by the consumer (drv_ring_pop). Callers MUST check shm_ring_push_ok /
# shm_ring_pop_ok before calling the matching mutator — the backpressure law
# (design §4: "compute pop-verdict on input ring AND push-verdict on output
# ring; only when BOTH ok, perform...") is enforced at the CALL SITE using
# the pure ring-verdict fns; drv_ring_push/drv_ring_pop trust the caller and
# just perform the prescribed shm writes.

fn shm_ring_push_ok(shm: [i64], r: i64) -> i32:
    val head: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_head_idx(r))
    val tail: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_tail_idx(r))
    ring_can_push(head, tail)

fn shm_ring_pop_ok(shm: [i64], r: i64) -> i32:
    val head: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_head_idx(r))
    val tail: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_tail_idx(r))
    if ring_empty(head, tail) == 1:
        return 0
    1

# Publish order (design §4): write payload words, then (fence — no-op on
# host), then advance TAIL.
fn drv_ring_push(shm: [i64], r: i64, w0: i64, w1: i64, w2: i64, w3: i64) -> [i64]:
    val tail: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_tail_idx(r))
    var s = shm
    s = shm_put(s, ring_slot_idx(r, tail, 0), w0)
    s = shm_put(s, ring_slot_idx(r, tail, 1), w1)
    s = shm_put(s, ring_slot_idx(r, tail, 2), w2)
    s = shm_put(s, ring_slot_idx(r, tail, 3), w3)
    s = shm_put(s, ring_tail_idx(r), tail + 1)
    s

# Read one word of the message at the HEAD slot, without mutating anything —
# the consume-order read half of "read TAIL -> fence -> read payload -> write
# HEAD" (§4).
fn drv_ring_peek_word(shm: [i64], r: i64, word: i64) -> i64:
    val head: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_head_idx(r))
    shm_get(shm, ring_slot_idx(r, head, word))

# Consume order tail: advance HEAD by one (the payload words must already
# have been read via drv_ring_peek_word before calling this).
fn drv_ring_pop(shm: [i64], r: i64) -> [i64]:
    val head: i64 = shm_get(shm, ring_head_idx(r))
    shm_put(shm, ring_head_idx(r), head + 1)

# ── buf pool driver (§5) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn buf_pool_alloc_slot(shm: [i64]) -> i64:
    val free_head: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_free_head_idx())
    val alloc_count: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx())
    buf_alloc_verdict(free_head, alloc_count)

fn drv_buf_alloc_commit(shm: [i64], slot: i64) -> [i64]:
    val new_head: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_next_idx(slot))
    var s = shm
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_next_idx(slot), BUF_IN_USE())
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_free_head_idx(), new_head)
    val cnt: i64 = shm_get(s, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx())
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx(), cnt + 1)
    s

fn buf_pool_free_ok(shm: [i64], slot: i64) -> i32:
    val next_val: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_next_idx(slot))
    val free_head: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_free_head_idx())
    val alloc_count: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx())
    buf_free_verdict_ok(buf_free_verdict(slot, next_val, free_head, alloc_count))

fn drv_buf_free_commit(shm: [i64], slot: i64) -> [i64]:
    if buf_pool_free_ok(shm, slot) == 0:
        return shm
    val free_head: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_free_head_idx())
    var s = shm
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_next_idx(slot), free_head)
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_free_head_idx(), slot)
    val cnt: i64 = shm_get(s, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx())
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx(), cnt - 1)
    s

# ── aggregate + scheduler helpers ──────────────────────────────────────────────

fn all_rings_empty(shm: [i64]) -> i32:
    var r: i64 = 0
    while r < ring_count():
        if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r) == 1:
            return 0
        r = r + 1
    1

fn pump_once(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    var s = shm
    s = hil_step(s)
    s = ftl_step(s)
    s = fil_step(s)
    s = nand_step(s)
    s

# Bounded drain helpers: try up to the 100000-step scheduler budget (design
# §8 / lane spec: "Budget exhaustion = FAIL"), then return whatever shm state
# was reached. Callers detect success/failure by re-checking the SAME
# predicate the drain was waiting on — this sidesteps returning a second
# "did it converge" value (see the tuple-avoidance note in the file header).
fn drain_until_ftl2hil_ready(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    # Waits for BOTH the ring (original condition) AND HIL's corostate
    # actually being CS_REAP (W4b addition — see file header "Deviations"):
    # CS_SUBMIT/CS_VERIFY advance every tick unconditionally, so a
    # completion can land in R_FTL2HIL on a tick where HIL isn't the phase
    # that would reap it. Without this second condition the selftest's one
    # explicit `hil_step(shm)` call right after this drain could land on a
    # SUBMIT/VERIFY pass-through instead of the reap, leaving the
    # completion unpopped. Same budget, same "whatever state was reached"
    # contract as before (see the comment above this fn group).
    var s = shm
    var i: i64 = 0
    while ((shm_ring_pop_ok(s, r_ftl2hil()) == 0) or (hc_get(s, host_corostate_idx(HIL_CORE())) != CS_REAP())) and i < 100000:
        s = pump_once(s)
        i = i + 1
    s

fn drain_until_all_empty(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    var s = shm
    var i: i64 = 0
    while all_rings_empty(s) == 0 and i < 100000:
        s = pump_once(s)
        i = i + 1
    s

# W4b addition: drives the corostate overlay the rest of the way to its
# terminal state (design §5 end-state oracle). drain_until_all_empty alone
# does not reach this — see the stage-5 comment at its call site.
fn drain_until_all_parked(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    var s = shm
    var i: i64 = 0
    while all_corostates_parked(s) == 0 and i < 100000:
        s = pump_once(s)
        i = i + 1
    s

# ── HIL submit path (host test driver only — NOT part of the round-robin
# scheduler; the ring-backpressure oracle needs submits callable back-to-back
# WITHOUT the scheduler running in between, per the lane spec) ──────────────

fn hil_can_submit(shm: [i64]) -> i32:
    shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_hil2ftl())

fn hil_submit_write(shm: [i64], lba: i64, tag: i64, data: i64) -> [i64]:
    if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
        return shm
    val slot: i64 = buf_pool_alloc_slot(shm)
    if slot == ipc_null_idx():
        return shm
    var s = shm
    s = drv_buf_alloc_commit(s, slot)
    s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_data_idx(slot), data)
    val w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(OP_WRITE(), tag, ST_OK())
    drv_ring_push(s, r_hil2ftl(), w0, lba, slot, 0)

fn hil_submit_read(shm: [i64], lba: i64, tag: i64) -> [i64]:
    if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
        return shm
    val slot: i64 = buf_pool_alloc_slot(shm)
    if slot == ipc_null_idx():
        return shm
    var s = shm
    s = drv_buf_alloc_commit(s, slot)
    val w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(OP_READ(), tag, ST_OK())
    drv_ring_push(s, r_hil2ftl(), w0, lba, slot, 0)

fn hil_submit_flush(shm: [i64], tag: i64) -> [i64]:
    if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
        return shm
    val w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(OP_FLUSH(), tag, ST_OK())
    drv_ring_push(shm, r_hil2ftl(), w0, 0, ipc_null_idx(), 0)

# ── core step functions (§8: "one message movement per call") — W4b:
# rewritten as corostate dispatchers (design §4). Every dataplane statement
# below is EXACTLY what used to live directly in hil_step/ftl_step/
# fil_step/nand_step; only the wrapping changed (file header "Deviations"
# explains the per-core phase mapping). ─────────────────────────────────────

# HIL CS_REAP phase body: consume ONE completion off R_FTL2HIL (if any) and
# free its buffer (if it held one — flush/bounds-fail completions may carry
# IPC_NULL_IDX or a valid never-used slot; both are handled uniformly).
# Unchanged from the pre-W4b hil_step body except the tail: instead of
# returning drv_ring_pop's result directly, it feeds that shm into the one
# CS_REAP->CS_VERIFY transition (design §4 "ending in exactly one
# transition").
fn hil_step_reap(shm: [i64], cs: i64) -> [i64]:
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
        return shm
    val buf_idx: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2hil(), 2)
    var s = shm
    if buf_idx != ipc_null_idx():
        if buf_pool_free_ok(s, buf_idx) == 1:
            s = drv_buf_free_commit(s, buf_idx)
    s = drv_ring_pop(s, r_ftl2hil())
    coro_do_transition(s, HIL_CORE(), cs, CS_VERIFY())

# HIL dispatcher (design §4/§6): CS_BOOT->CS_SUBMIT stands in for the rv32
# hart-release gate this harness doesn't have (file header). CS_SUBMIT and
# CS_VERIFY are pass-through phases (see file header "Deviations" for why);
# CS_REAP is the only phase with a data-dependent guard, gated on the exact
# same shm_ring_pop_ok check the original hil_step used.
fn hil_step(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    val cs: i64 = hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(HIL_CORE()))
    if cs == CS_BOOT():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, HIL_CORE(), cs, CS_SUBMIT())
    if cs == CS_SUBMIT():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, HIL_CORE(), cs, CS_REAP())
    if cs == CS_REAP():
        return hil_step_reap(shm, cs)
    if cs == CS_VERIFY():
        val halt_word: i64 = shm_get(shm, IPC_HALT_IDX())
        if halt_word == 1:
            return coro_do_transition(shm, HIL_CORE(), cs, CS_HALT_DRAIN())
        return coro_do_transition(shm, HIL_CORE(), cs, CS_SUBMIT())
    if cs == CS_HALT_DRAIN():
        return coro_halt_drain_phase(shm, HIL_CORE(), cs)
    if cs == CS_PARKED():
        return shm
    print "  FAIL: HIL corostate word out of range"
    exit(1)
    shm

# FTL CS_IDLE phase body (unchanged from the pre-W4b ftl_step body): up-pump
# (FIL completion -> HIL) takes priority over down-pump (HIL request -> FTL
# routing); still at most one message movement total.
fn ftl_step_body(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_fil2ftl()) == 1:
        if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 1:
            val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2ftl(), 0)
            val w1: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2ftl(), 1)
            val w2: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2ftl(), 2)
            val w3: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2ftl(), 3)
            var s = shm
            s = drv_ring_push(s, r_ftl2hil(), w0, w1, w2, w3)
            return drv_ring_pop(s, r_fil2ftl())
        return shm
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_hil2ftl()) == 0:
        return shm
    val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_hil2ftl(), 0)
    val w1: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_hil2ftl(), 1)
    val w2: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_hil2ftl(), 2)
    val opcode: i64 = msg_w0_opcode(w0)
    val tag: i64 = msg_w0_tag(w0)
    val routed: i64 = ftl_route_opcode(opcode)
    if routed == -1:
        # OP_FLUSH completes at FTL directly (design §4/§8); any other
        # opcode landing here is a defensive fail-closed case (never
        # produced by hil_submit_*, kept for hardening honesty).
        if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
            return shm
        var out_status: i64 = ST_OK()
        if opcode != OP_FLUSH():
            out_status = ST_ERR()
        val out_w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(opcode, tag, out_status)
        var s = shm
        s = drv_ring_push(s, r_ftl2hil(), out_w0, w1, w2, 0)
        return drv_ring_pop(s, r_hil2ftl())
    val ppn: i64 = ftl_map_ppn(w1)
    if ppn == -1:
        # LBA out of range: synthesize ST_BOUNDS directly, bypass FIL/NAND.
        if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
            return shm
        val out_w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(opcode, tag, ST_BOUNDS())
        var s = shm
        s = drv_ring_push(s, r_ftl2hil(), out_w0, w1, w2, 0)
        return drv_ring_pop(s, r_hil2ftl())
    if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_ftl2fil()) == 0:
        return shm
    val out_w0b: i64 = msg_w0_pack(routed, tag, ST_OK())
    var s = shm
    s = drv_ring_push(s, r_ftl2fil(), out_w0b, ppn, w2, 0)
    drv_ring_pop(s, r_hil2ftl())

# FTL CS_IDLE dispatch wrapper: runs the unchanged body, then picks the one
# outgoing transition (self-loop, unless halt is observed — file header
# "Deviations" explains why CS_PUMP_FWD/CS_PUMP_BACK are not labeled here).
fn ftl_step_idle(shm: [i64], cs: i64) -> [i64]:
    val s: [i64] = ftl_step_body(shm)
    val halt_word: i64 = shm_get(s, IPC_HALT_IDX())
    if halt_word == 1:
        return coro_do_transition(s, FTL_CORE(), cs, CS_HALT_DRAIN())
    coro_do_transition(s, FTL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())

fn ftl_step(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    val cs: i64 = hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(FTL_CORE()))
    if cs == CS_BOOT():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, FTL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_IDLE():
        return ftl_step_idle(shm, cs)
    if cs == CS_PUMP_FWD():
        # Unreached by this harness's simplified overlay (file header
        # "Deviations"); kept for full vocabulary coverage, same hardening-
        # honesty convention as nand_step_body's NOP_ERASE branch below.
        return coro_do_transition(shm, FTL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_PUMP_BACK():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, FTL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_HALT_DRAIN():
        return coro_halt_drain_phase(shm, FTL_CORE(), cs)
    if cs == CS_PARKED():
        return shm
    print "  FAIL: FTL corostate word out of range"
    exit(1)
    shm

# FIL CS_IDLE phase body (unchanged from the pre-W4b fil_step body): up-pump
# (NAND completion -> FTL) takes priority over down-pump (FTL request ->
# NAND routing).
fn fil_step_body(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_nand2fil()) == 1:
        if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_fil2ftl()) == 1:
            val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_nand2fil(), 0)
            val w1: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_nand2fil(), 1)
            val w2: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_nand2fil(), 2)
            val w3: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_nand2fil(), 3)
            val opcode: i64 = msg_w0_opcode(w0)
            val tag: i64 = msg_w0_tag(w0)
            val st: i64 = msg_w0_status(w0)
            val out_status: i64 = fil_status_of_nand(st)
            val out_w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(opcode, tag, out_status)
            var s = shm
            s = drv_ring_push(s, r_fil2ftl(), out_w0, w1, w2, w3)
            return drv_ring_pop(s, r_nand2fil())
        return shm
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_ftl2fil()) == 0:
        return shm
    val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2fil(), 0)
    val w1: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2fil(), 1)
    val w2: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2fil(), 2)
    val w3: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2fil(), 3)
    val opcode: i64 = msg_w0_opcode(w0)
    val tag: i64 = msg_w0_tag(w0)
    val nand_op: i64 = fil_route_opcode(opcode)
    if nand_op == -1:
        # Fail-closed: an unroutable opcode reaching FIL — bump the shared
        # error counter and drop rather than forward garbage to NAND or
        # wedge the ring forever (design §2 rule 4: never wrap, never
        # clamp-and-continue). Unreachable via hil_submit_*/ftl_step in this
        # harness; kept for hardening honesty.
        val errc: i64 = shm_get(shm, ipc_err_count_idx())
        var s = shm
        s = shm_put(s, ipc_err_count_idx(), errc + 1)
        return drv_ring_pop(s, r_ftl2fil())
    if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_fil2nand()) == 0:
        return shm
    val out_w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(nand_op, tag, ST_OK())
    var s = shm
    s = drv_ring_push(s, r_fil2nand(), out_w0, w1, w2, w3)
    drv_ring_pop(s, r_ftl2fil())

# FIL CS_IDLE dispatch wrapper — same shape as ftl_step_idle.
fn fil_step_idle(shm: [i64], cs: i64) -> [i64]:
    val s: [i64] = fil_step_body(shm)
    val halt_word: i64 = shm_get(s, IPC_HALT_IDX())
    if halt_word == 1:
        return coro_do_transition(s, FIL_CORE(), cs, CS_HALT_DRAIN())
    coro_do_transition(s, FIL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())

fn fil_step(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    val cs: i64 = hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(FIL_CORE()))
    if cs == CS_BOOT():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, FIL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_IDLE():
        return fil_step_idle(shm, cs)
    if cs == CS_PUMP_FWD():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, FIL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_PUMP_BACK():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, FIL_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_HALT_DRAIN():
        return coro_halt_drain_phase(shm, FIL_CORE(), cs)
    if cs == CS_PARKED():
        return shm
    print "  FAIL: FIL corostate word out of range"
    exit(1)
    shm

# NAND CS_IDLE phase body (unchanged from the pre-W4b nand_step body):
# consume ONE request off R_FIL2NAND, apply it to the NAND-state/data
# region + buf-pool data staging words, push ONE completion to R_NAND2FIL.
fn nand_step_body(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_fil2nand()) == 0:
        return shm
    if shm_ring_push_ok(shm, r_nand2fil()) == 0:
        return shm
    val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2nand(), 0)
    val ppn: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2nand(), 1)
    val buf_idx: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2nand(), 2)
    val block: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_fil2nand(), 3)
    val opcode: i64 = msg_w0_opcode(w0)
    val tag: i64 = msg_w0_tag(w0)

    var s = shm
    var out_status: i64 = ST_ERR()

    if opcode == NOP_PROG():
        if nand_ppn_valid(ppn) == 0:
            out_status = ST_BOUNDS()
        else:
            val cur_state: i64 = shm_get(s, nand_state_idx(ppn))
            if nand_program_verdict(cur_state) == NAND_PROGRAM_OK():
                val data_word: i64 = shm_get(s, buf_pool_data_idx(buf_idx))
                s = shm_put(s, nand_state_idx(ppn), 1)
                s = shm_put(s, nand_data_idx(ppn), data_word)
                out_status = ST_OK()
            else:
                out_status = ST_MEDIA()

    if opcode == NOP_READ():
        if nand_ppn_valid(ppn) == 0:
            out_status = ST_BOUNDS()
        else:
            val cur_state: i64 = shm_get(s, nand_state_idx(ppn))
            var data_val: i64 = NAND_ERASED_DATA()
            if nand_read_verdict(cur_state) == NAND_READ_OK():
                data_val = shm_get(s, nand_data_idx(ppn))
            s = shm_put(s, buf_pool_data_idx(buf_idx), data_val)
            out_status = ST_OK()

    if opcode == NOP_ERASE():
        # Not reachable via this harness (no FTL/FIL path emits OP_ERASE —
        # HIL only issues WRITE/READ/FLUSH); implemented for opcode-table
        # completeness/hardening honesty, not exercised by the 5 selftest
        # oracles below.
        if nand_block_valid(block) == 0:
            out_status = ST_BOUNDS()
        else:
            val first: i64 = nand_block_first_ppn(block)
            val last: i64 = nand_block_last_ppn(block)
            var p: i64 = first
            while p <= last:
                s = shm_put(s, nand_state_idx(p), NAND_STATE_ERASED())
                p = p + 1
            out_status = ST_OK()

    val out_w0: i64 = msg_w0_pack(opcode, tag, out_status)
    s = drv_ring_push(s, r_nand2fil(), out_w0, ppn, buf_idx, block)
    drv_ring_pop(s, r_fil2nand())

# NAND CS_IDLE dispatch wrapper — same shape as ftl_step_idle/fil_step_idle.
fn nand_step_idle(shm: [i64], cs: i64) -> [i64]:
    val s: [i64] = nand_step_body(shm)
    val halt_word: i64 = shm_get(s, IPC_HALT_IDX())
    if halt_word == 1:
        return coro_do_transition(s, NAND_CORE(), cs, CS_HALT_DRAIN())
    coro_do_transition(s, NAND_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())

fn nand_step(shm: [i64]) -> [i64]:
    val cs: i64 = hc_get(shm, host_corostate_idx(NAND_CORE()))
    if cs == CS_BOOT():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, NAND_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_IDLE():
        return nand_step_idle(shm, cs)
    if cs == CS_PUMP_FWD():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, NAND_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_PUMP_BACK():
        return coro_do_transition(shm, NAND_CORE(), cs, CS_IDLE())
    if cs == CS_HALT_DRAIN():
        return coro_halt_drain_phase(shm, NAND_CORE(), cs)
    if cs == CS_PARKED():
        return shm
    print "  FAIL: NAND corostate word out of range"
    exit(1)
    shm

# ── 5-stage dataplane selftest (design §8, lane spec L5b) ─────────────────────

fn ipc_fourcore_selftest() -> i32:
    var shm: [i64] = shm_new()
    var tag: i64 = 0
    val lbas: [i64] = [5, 100, 3071]

    # Stage 1a: write 3 LBAs with the fixed data oracle hil_expect_data(lba).
    var idx: i64 = 0
    while idx < 3:
        val lba: i64 = lbas[idx]
        if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
            print "  FAIL: stage1 write submit unexpectedly rejected"
            return 1
        shm = hil_submit_write(shm, lba, tag, hil_expect_data(lba))
        shm = drain_until_ftl2hil_ready(shm)
        if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
            print "  FAIL: step budget exhausted awaiting write completion"
            return 1
        val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2hil(), 0)
        if msg_w0_tag(w0) != tag:
            print "  FAIL: write completion tag mismatch (FIFO order broken)"
            return 1
        if msg_w0_status(w0) != ST_OK():
            print "  FAIL: write completion status != ST_OK"
            return 1
        shm = hil_step(shm)
        if idx == 0:
            # Oracle (a) (design §5, W4b): the FIRST write's full HIL
            # journey must show the canonical corostate sequence
            # CS_BOOT->CS_SUBMIT->CS_REAP->CS_VERIFY, still present in the
            # last-16 transition trace ring at this exact checkpoint (this
            # journey logs 15 total entries across all 4 cores — verified
            # by execution — one under the 16-slot cap, so nothing has been
            # evicted yet).
            if hil_seq_check(shm) == 0:
                print "  FAIL: HIL canonical transition sequence BOOT->SUBMIT->REAP->VERIFY not found in trace ring"
                return 1
        tag = tag + 1
        idx = idx + 1

    # Stage 1b: flush, assert ST_OK.
    if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
        print "  FAIL: stage1 flush submit unexpectedly rejected"
        return 1
    shm = hil_submit_flush(shm, tag)
    shm = drain_until_ftl2hil_ready(shm)
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
        print "  FAIL: step budget exhausted awaiting flush completion"
        return 1
    if msg_w0_status(drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2hil(), 0)) != ST_OK():
        print "  FAIL: flush completion status != ST_OK"
        return 1
    shm = hil_step(shm)
    tag = tag + 1

    # Stage 1c: read back all 3 LBAs, assert exact data values.
    idx = 0
    while idx < 3:
        val lba: i64 = lbas[idx]
        if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
            print "  FAIL: stage1 read submit unexpectedly rejected"
            return 1
        shm = hil_submit_read(shm, lba, tag)
        shm = drain_until_ftl2hil_ready(shm)
        if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
            print "  FAIL: step budget exhausted awaiting read completion"
            return 1
        val w0: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2hil(), 0)
        val buf_idx: i64 = drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2hil(), 2)
        if msg_w0_tag(w0) != tag:
            print "  FAIL: read completion tag mismatch (FIFO order broken)"
            return 1
        if msg_w0_status(w0) != ST_OK():
            print "  FAIL: read completion status != ST_OK"
            return 1
        if shm_get(shm, buf_pool_data_idx(buf_idx)) != hil_expect_data(lba):
            print "  FAIL: read data mismatch against hil_expect_data(lba)"
            return 1
        shm = hil_step(shm)
        tag = tag + 1
        idx = idx + 1

    # Stage 2: read an out-of-range LBA -> completion status ST_BOUNDS.
    if hil_can_submit(shm) == 0:
        print "  FAIL: stage2 OOB read submit unexpectedly rejected"
        return 1
    shm = hil_submit_read(shm, 9999, tag)
    shm = drain_until_ftl2hil_ready(shm)
    if shm_ring_pop_ok(shm, r_ftl2hil()) == 0:
        print "  FAIL: step budget exhausted awaiting OOB-read completion"
        return 1
    if msg_w0_status(drv_ring_peek_word(shm, r_ftl2hil(), 0)) != ST_BOUNDS():
        print "  FAIL: OOB read (lba=9999) completion status != ST_BOUNDS"
        return 1
    shm = hil_step(shm)
    tag = tag + 1

    # Stage 3: 9 writes back-to-back with NO scheduler steps in between —
    # ring depth is 8, so the 9th submit must be rejected (backoff verdict).
    var accepted: i64 = 0
    var i3: i64 = 0
    while i3 < 9:
        val ok: i32 = hil_can_submit(shm)
        if i3 < 8:
            if ok == 0:
                print "  FAIL: an early back-to-back submit was unexpectedly rejected"
                return 1
            shm = hil_submit_write(shm, 200 + i3, tag, hil_expect_data(200 + i3))
            tag = tag + 1
            accepted = accepted + 1
        else:
            if ok != 0:
                print "  FAIL: 9th back-to-back submit unexpectedly accepted (expected ring-full backoff)"
                return 1
        i3 = i3 + 1
    if accepted != 8:
        print "  FAIL: stage3 accepted-submit count != 8"
        return 1

    # Stage 4: drain all in-flight traffic, then assert no buf-pool leak and
    # a complete 16-slot free-list.
    shm = drain_until_all_empty(shm)
    if all_rings_empty(shm) == 0:
        print "  FAIL: step budget exhausted draining stage3 traffic"
        return 1
    if shm_get(shm, buf_pool_alloc_count_idx()) != 0:
        print "  FAIL: buf pool ALLOC_COUNT != 0 after full reap (leak)"
        return 1
    var visited: [i64] = [0 for i in 0..buf_pool_capacity()]
    var cursor: i64 = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_free_head_idx())
    var walk_steps: i64 = 0
    while cursor != ipc_null_idx():
        if walk_steps > buf_pool_capacity():
            print "  FAIL: buf pool free-list walk did not terminate"
            return 1
        if buf_slot_valid(cursor) == 0:
            print "  FAIL: buf pool free-list walk hit an out-of-range slot"
            return 1
        if visited[cursor] != 0:
            print "  FAIL: buf pool free-list walk revisited a slot (cycle)"
            return 1
        visited[cursor] = 1
        cursor = shm_get(shm, buf_pool_next_idx(cursor))
        walk_steps = walk_steps + 1
    var total: i64 = 0
    var vi: i64 = 0
    while vi < buf_pool_capacity():
        total = total + visited[vi]
        vi = vi + 1
    if total != buf_pool_capacity():
        print "  FAIL: buf pool free-list walk did not reach all 16 slots"
        return 1

    # Stage 5: halt + drain, assert done.
    shm = shm_put(shm, IPC_HALT_IDX(), 1)
    shm = drain_until_all_empty(shm)
    val halt_word: i64 = shm_get(shm, IPC_HALT_IDX())
    val empties: i32 = all_rings_empty(shm)
    if core_should_halt(halt_word, empties) != 1:
        print "  FAIL: halt+drain did not reach the done condition"
        return 1

    # Oracle (b) (design §5, W4b): drive the corostate overlay the rest of
    # the way to its terminal state and assert all four corostate words end
    # at CS_PARKED. drain_until_all_empty alone does not guarantee this:
    # stage 4 already fully drained the rings, so drain_until_all_empty's
    # while-condition is false on entry here and it runs zero extra
    # pump_once ticks — this harness has no real hart-release gate, so its
    # CS_BOOT exit stands in for one (file header), and likewise needs its
    # own explicit drain here for every core to observe the halt flag and
    # walk CS_IDLE/CS_VERIFY -> CS_HALT_DRAIN -> CS_PARKED.
    shm = drain_until_all_parked(shm)
    if all_corostates_parked(shm) == 0:
        print "  FAIL: end-state oracle: not all 4 corostate words reached CS_PARKED after halt+drain"
        return 1

    if shm_get(shm, ipc_err_count_idx()) != 0:
        print "  FAIL: IPC_ERR_COUNT nonzero after a clean run"
        return 1

    0

fn main():
    val fail = ipc_fourcore_selftest()
    if fail == 0:
        print "IPC FOURCORE CHECK PASS"
    else:
        print "IPC FOURCORE CHECK FAIL"
        exit(1)
